<a href="#5" id="5">Given a credibility base {a mathematical formula}C, the function {a mathematical formula}rel(C) returns the set of agent identifiers that are sources of credibility elements in {a mathematical formula}C, i.e., {a mathematical formula}rel(C)={S:[P>Q,S] ∈ C}.</a>
<a href="#6" id="6">This function will be used to determine the set of agent identifiers that represents the reliability of an argument.</a>
<a href="#7" id="7">As we will show below, an argument will be composed of a set of credibility objects, and to obtain its reliability the sources of those objects will be considered.</a>
<a href="#8" id="8">Each credibility element that can be inferred from a credibility base {a mathematical formula}C will have an argument associated that supports it, and such argument will contain the reliability information for that inference.</a>
<a href="#9" id="9">This reliability information will be used for comparing arguments supporting contradictory conclusions.</a>
<a href="#10" id="10">An argument is a minimal set of credibility objects as defined next.</a>
